What is Framwork? How it work in C++?

Let’s keep it concrete and minimal. 
Here’s a tiny example using the Qt framework to show how a framework controls the flow and calls your code.

Minimal Qt Framework Example

#include <QCoreApplication>
#include <QTimer>
#include <QObject>
#include <QDebug>

class MyApp : public QObject {
    Q_OBJECT
public:
    MyApp() {
        // Framework will call this later via event loop
        QTimer::singleShot(1000, this, &MyApp::onTimeout);
    }

public slots:
    void onTimeout() {
        qDebug() << "Framework called my function!";
        QCoreApplication::quit();
    }
};

int main(int argc, char *argv[]) {
    QCoreApplication app(argc, argv);

    MyApp myApp;

    return app.exec();  // 👈 Framework takes control here
}

🔍 What’s happening
    app.exec() starts Qt’s event loop
    After that, you don’t control the flow anymore
    The framework waits for events (timers, UI, signals)
    Then it calls your function:
    void onTimeout()

👉 You never call onTimeout() directly
👉 Qt calls it → that’s the framework behavior

⚖️ Compare with normal C++ (no framework)
int main() {
    std::cout << "Hello\n";
}

Here:

    You control everything
    No event loop
    No callbacks
    🧠 Key takeaway

In a C++ framework like Qt:

You write handlers (slots / callbacks)
Framework runs the program
Framework decides when your code runs

